name: Qingqing Cao
tweet: 4/5 We use a hardware power meter to measure energy accurately and quantify the error (>20%) of existing software measurements. We find current software measurements without calibration are inaccurate and cause misleading design choices.  #SustaiNLP #EMNLP2020 #NLProc

name: Qingqing Cao
tweet: 3/5 Existing utilization-based software methods do not address issues like power lag, tail energy issues. Non-utilization behaviors such as data movement in GPUs also cause energy. Resource profiling should avoid high overhead. #SustaiNLP #EMNLP2020 #NLProc

name: Qingqing Cao
tweet: 2/5 Accurate energy measurement is critical for choosing and training large NLP models and deploying to battery-powered mobile devices.  #SustaiNLP #EMNLP2020 #NLProc  https://t.co/zxjQyg2Qsy

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Q (@sivareddyg ): You take sentences and introduce negation---was this automated? A: Our annotators add negation to the main verb. We check the constructions are semantically valid. #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Hossain: We analyze negations w.r.t frequency, importance and alignment. We create a corpus of 4500 text-hypothesis pairs that contain negation. We find that transformers (RoBERTa, XLNet, BERT) are unable to solve pairs with negation. /4 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Hossain: We find negation is not represented. One can often ignore negation and still make the right inference judgement. /3 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Hossain: Negation is a frequent phenomenon in general-purpose English. We take a look at negations in RTE, SNLI, MNLI. /2 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: #emnlp2020  An Analysis of Natural Language Inference Benchmarks through the Lens of Negation Md Mosharaf Hossain, Venelin Kovatchev, Pranoy Dutta, Tiffany Kao, Elizabeth Wei and Eduardo Blanco Paper:  https://t.co/oPc92K1kkx Talk:  https://t.co/u8ZdYBtYZr /1

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Q (Alicia Parrish): Are models matching the original annotator's label instead of what the gold label ends up being? A: I checked both and the trend is similar on both. #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Q (Nicholas Lourie): One finding is that SOTA models do poorly on low-agreement examples. Did you try training on soft examples that average annotations? A: We didn't try the soft-label method, future work can explore this area. #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Nie: We collect 100 annotations per example, for over 4500 examples for abductive NLI, SNLI, MNLI. High human disagreement exists in a noticeable amount of examples, and models cant recover the distribution. They barely beat a random guess on low-agreement data. /7 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Nie: In this work, we want to understand collective human opinions on natural language inference (NLI) and adaptive inference.  /5 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Nie: In exams, correct labels are usually authoritative. NLP tasks may require pragmatic inference, and the gold label can be debatable.  /4 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Nie: However as NLP models become stronger, researchers look at more challenging tasks. This creates a divergence. Exams remain objective, tasks become more subjective and uncertain /3 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Nie: We have all suffered through examinations. Surprisingly most NLP tasks are conducted with a similar mental model /2 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: #emnlp2020 What Can We Learn from Collective Human Opinions on Natural Language Inference Data? Yixin Nie, Xiang Zhou and Mohit Bansal Paper:  https://t.co/GNObHsKprG Talk: https://t.co/X62EEj0vzQ @EasonNie @XiangZhou14 @mohitban47  /1

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Fisher: Bias is also reduced significantly, measured by having the model trying to predict controversial features e.g. gender and religion. #emnlp2020  /8

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Fisher: Using this method you can achieve comparable results as with biased embeddings, whereas previous debiasing methods see a significant drop in performance. #emnlp2020  /7

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Fisher: Sometimes adding this info is not controversial i.e. if predicting whether or not a person speaks French, it is uncontroversial to know that they are French. Mitigate this by simply adding this info back in hand-selected cases. #emnlp2020  /6

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Fisher: Use an adversarial loss in order to make it difficult for the model to be able to predict sensitive attributes about an entity i.e. the model can’t predict if a person is male or female #emnlp2020  /5

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Fisher: Introduce discriminator relations: e.g. if person is male, they have a has_gender MALE triple #emnlp2020  /4

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Fisher: Bias in this work concerned with how gender, religion, ethnicity, and nationality relate to a person’s profession #emnlp2020  /3

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Fisher:  Problem - Knowledge graph embeddings can encode potentially harmful social biases, e.g. related to gender and profession Goal - Develop a method to alter the training of knowledge graph embeddings to remove this bias #emnlp2020  /2

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: 🚨#emnlp2020🚨 Debiasing Knowledge Graph Embeddings Joseph Fisher, Arpit Mittal, Dave Palfrey, Christos Christodoulopoulos 📰Paper:  https://t.co/uQoKosudL5 🗣️Talk:  https://t.co/jIy2v6pCEV /1

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Ben-David: PERL and R-PERL outperform baselines by a large margin on sentiment analysis, including a more challenging domain adaptation setup to airline reviews. They also outperform baselines on in-domain experiments as well #emnlp2020  /8

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Ben-David: Also have regularized PERL (R-PERL): initialize final layer with pre-trained embeddings, and take into account the pivot’s semantics #emnlp2020  /7

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Ben-David: Pivot-based fine-tuning involves masking pivot features with high probability, non-pivots with low probability. Then, for pivot-features train to predict the actual feature. Non-pivots are trained to simply predict that feature is not a pivot feature. #emnlp2020  /6

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Ben-David:  1⃣: Train masked language modeling (MLM) on data from a broad domain 2⃣:  fine-tune model on unlabelled data from source and target domains with pivot-based MLM 3⃣:  fine tune model on downstream task with labelled data from source domain #emnlp2020  /5

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Ben-David: Approach domain adaptation from the perspective of pivot features -- features which are frequent in source and target domains and important for the task. #emnlp2020  /4

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Ben-David: This work tries to address this problem of unsupervised domain adaptation -- unlabelled data from a source and target domain, labelled data from only source domain. #emnlp2020  /3

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Ben-David: What happens when the training and test set don't follow the same underlying distribution? Extreme degradation in performance. #emnlp2020  /2

tweet: Galkin: Limited datasets for testing link prediction with hyper-relational KGs, so propose WikiData-50K: A family of hyper-relational datasets based on wikidata #emnlp2020  /7

tweet: Galkin: Evaluate StarE on link prediction - do qualifiers improve the accuracy of subject/object prediction of a fact? How many qualifiers do you need? #emnlp2020  /6

tweet: Galkin: Develop notion of sparse qualifier representation to facilitate efficient storage #emnlp2020  /5

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Gao: Achieves significant improvements across languages on all baselines which don’t use contextualized word embeddings #emnlp2020  /6

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Gao: Performance is comparable to baselines for named entity recognition on multiple languages, achieves new state of the art on NER in Dutch 🇳🇱 #emnlp2020  /5

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Gao: Decompose the scoring function into a neural net component and a graphical component for computational efficiency Training objective should encourage a correct ranking for each pair of outputs: use max margin hinge loss (Neural SampleRank(NSR)) #emnlp2020  /4

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Gao: Skip-chains - long-range factors connecting recurring tokens To avoid large computational cost, use Gibbs sampling with annealing for approximate inference #emnlp2020  /3

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Gao: Most prominently used graphical model is the Linear Chain CRF, but can more complex and expressive CRFs be used? Introduce a new inductive bias: different occurrences of the same token often have same label #emnlp2020  /2

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Lukasik: Yields statistically significant improvements over several label smoothing baselines on machine translation #emnlp2020  /5

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Lukasik: Select sequences from a large corpus of reference sequences which have high semantic similarity score and high BLEU score with the target sequence. #emnlp2020  /4

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Lukasik: Propose a technique which smooths over well-formed relevant sequences which are semantically similar to the target sequence, improving over state-of-the-art techniques #emnlp2020  /3

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Lukasik: Label smoothing is good for regularization, but challenging to apply in seq2seq settings with large output spaces Existing techniques are insufficient: lead to samples which are not well-formed or semantically related to the target sequences #emnlp2020  /2

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Ding: HyperGAT is evaluated on 5 text classification tasks and compared to word-embedding, sequence-based, and graph-based classification methods; achieves better performance with lower computational resources than existing graph neural networks #emnlp2020  /5

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Ding: HyperGAT is based on a dual attention mechanism to support representation learning on text hypergraphs #emnlp2020  /4

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Ding: Research question - Is it possible to acquire more expressive power with less computational consumption for graph-based text classification? Solution - Model with document-level hypergraphs, namely hypergraph attention networks (HyperGAT) #emnlp2020  /3

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Ding: Graph neural networks for text classification have critical limitations: namely, their expressive power is limited as high-order word interactions should be considered. They are also computationally expensive #emnlp2020  /2

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Baly: Removing the source bias leads to significant improvements on the task of article bias prediction, triplet loss pre-training is better than domain adversarial training #emnlp2020  /6

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Baly: Try to remove the source bias via a domain adversarial loss on the article sources Additionally, try triplet loss pre-training on the article sources #emnlp2020  /5

name: Dustin Wright
tweet: Baly: To prevent models from learning to predict the source as opposed to bias signal, split data based on the media source Media-based splitting of the dataset shows that the problem is non-trivial, with low performance for both LSTMs and BERT #emnlp2020  /4

tweet: Baly: Media bias - perceived bias of news producers, can be systemic or as a part of political ideology (left, center, or right) Important to detect bias of news media to promote healthy public debate, ensure quality in news media, etc. #emnlp2020  /2

tweet: Kim: If you have any thoughts or feedback, please let us know!   (Talk ends with a picture of a really cute cat)  /11 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Kim: So what do we need to solve COGS? Maybe pretraining, multi-task learning, meta-learning, tree-structured models can help, or maybe grounded language learning can help identify primitives and atomic units of composition. /9 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Kim: 2) Do models find structural generalization more difficult than lexical generalization?   Answer: Yes, performance on structural generalization is especially poor.  However,  even success on lexical generalization seems idiosyncratic. /8 #emnlp2020  https://t.co/ZruYH8dtmH

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Kim: Questions we ask:   1) Do popular neural models (LSTM/Transformer) generalize compositionally?   Answer: Not really. Performance is overall poor on the generalization set, with high variation over random seeds /7 #emnlp2020  https://t.co/ZaAM82gpmj

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Kim: (a) Lexical generalization requires a novel composition of a known lexical item and a known structure. (b) Structural generalization requires a novel composition of known structures /6 #emnlp2020  https://t.co/WnOuUEAk8U

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Kim: COG target generalizations fall into two broad categories depending on the type of composition that is required: lexical and structural /6 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Kim: COG tests for 21 generalizations inspired by human language research. An example is subject to object generalization. In the training set,`hedgehog’ is used as a grammatical subject. The generalization set requires interpreting `hedgehog’ in the object position./5 #emnlp2020  https://t.co/hGOUVDFWCw

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Kim: To test for out-of-domain linguistic generalization exploiting compositionality, we propose COGS. COGS is a semantic parsing task from English sentences to logical forms, characterized by systematic gaps between training/evaluation sets. /4 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Kim: Current ML/NLP models perform well on in-domain generalization but poorly on out-of-domain generalization /3 #emnlp2020

name: Abhilasha Ravichander
tweet: Kim: Humans can interpret expressions they have never encountered before by composing the meanings of the parts they already know /2 #emnlp2020
